          "body": "When Paul resumes at 3:14, his prayer has three escalating petitions and one ultimate goal. **First**, that the Father would strengthen the readers *with power through His Spirit in the inner man* (3:16) — the deepest interior, the seat of will and desire. **Second**, *so that Christ may dwell in your hearts through faith* (3:17) — *katoikeo* is the verb for permanent residence, not visitation; Paul prays that the indwelling Christ would settle in, take possession, become at home. **Third**, that being *rooted and grounded in love* (3:17) — botanical and architectural metaphors stacked — they would *comprehend with all the saints* (3:18) the four dimensions of Christ's love and *know the love of Christ which surpasses knowledge* (3:19). The ultimate goal is staggering: *that you may be filled up to all the fullness of God* (3:19, *pleroma tou theou*). No prayer in the New Testament asks for more."
